: The Reunion]]''\n| Guest\n| [[ITV2]]\n| 1 episode; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n| 2018\u2013\n| ''[[How To Get A Good Night\u2019s Sleep]]''\n| Co-presenter\n| [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]\n| 1 series; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Celebrity Gogglebox]]''\n| TV Watcher\n| [[Channel 4]]\n| with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|}\n;Film\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]''\n| Bigmouth Executive & Forge (Re-dubbed voice)\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys D'Movie]]''\n| [[RT\u00c9]] newsreader\n| Cameo role\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Wonder Park]]''\n| Uncle Tony (Re-dubbed voice)\n| \n|}\n\n;Radio\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2003\u20132009\n| ''[[BBC Radio 5 Live|The Eamonn Holmes Show]]''\n| Presenter\n| Sports show on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]\n|-\n| 2005\u2013??\n| ''[[Magic 105.4 FM|Sunday Afternoons]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/491109/magic-fm-signs-eamonn-holmes-present-sunday-show|title=Magic FM signs Eamonn Holmes to present Sunday show|website=Campaignlive.co.uk|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304073511/http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/491109/magic-fm-signs-eamonn-holmes-present-sunday-show|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| Presenter\n| Sundays, 4{{snd}}7{{nbsp}}pm on [[Magic 105.4 FM|Magic FM]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''The Michael Parkinson Show''\n| Guest presenter\n| [[BBC Radio 2]] show\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Let's Talk with Eamonn Holmes''\n| Presenter\n| Sundays, 11{{nbsp}}am{{snd}}1{{nbsp}}pm on [[Talkradio]]\n|-\n| 2018\u20132020\n| ''Drivetime with Eamonn Holmes''\n| Presenter\n| Weekdays, 4{{snd}}7{{nbsp}}pm on [[Talkradio]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and honours==\nHolmes was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to broadcasting in the [[2018 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2017-12-29/ringo-starr-and-barry-gibb-to-be-knighted-in-new-year-honours/|title=Ringo Starr and Barry Gibb knighted in New Year Honours|work=ITV News}}</ref> He collected his OBE from [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 1 June 2018.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Group !! Award !! Result\n|-\n| 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011\n| rowspan=2|[[TRIC Awards]]\n| Satellite/Digital TV Personality\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2013\n| News Presenter/Reporter\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Legends of Industry Award\n| Services to Broadcasting and Journalism\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[TRIC Awards]]\n| News Presenter/Reporter\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[TRIC Awards]]\n| News Presenter\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0391810|name=Eamonn Holmes}}\n*[http://www.officialeamonnholmes.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holmes, Eamonn}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 5 Live presenters]]\n[[Category:British game show hosts]]\n[[Category:British sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Irish game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Irish television presenters]]\n[[Category:British television presenters]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Belfast]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Malachy's College]]\n[[Category:Sky newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:GMTV presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:Television presenters from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:UTV (TV channel)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish television presenter}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Eamonn Holmes<br /><small>[[Order of the British Empire|OBE]]</small>\n| image              = Eamon Holmes (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Holmes in 2013\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1959|12|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Belfast]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishnews.com/lifestyle/2018/06/06/news/eamonn-holmes-says-wife-ruth-trying-to-fatten-me-up-so-nobody-else-wants-me--1345681/|title=Eamonn Holmes says wife Ruth 'trying to fatten me up so nobody else wants me'|date=6 June 2018|website=The Irish News|accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref> Northern Ireland\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Gabrielle Holmes|1985|2005}} <br /> {{marriage|[[Ruth Langsford]]|2010}}\n| nationality        = Irish \n| occupation         = [[Television presenter|Broadcaster]], journalist\n| employer           = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]<br />[[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]\n| television         = ''[[GMTV]]'' \u2022 ''[[Sunrise (Sky News)|Sunrise]]'' \u2022 ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' \u2022 ''[[Songs of Praise]]'' \u2022 ''[[Gift Wrapped (game show)|Gift Wrapped]]'' \u2022 ''[[Eamonn & Ruth: How the Other Half Lives|How the Other Half Lives]]'' \u2022 ''[[It's Not Me, It's You (game show)|It's Not Me, It's You]]'' \u2022 ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''\n| years_active       = 1979\u2013present\n| children           = liam dettmer\n| height             = {{convert|5|ft|11.80|in|m|sigfig=3}}{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n}}\n\n'''Eamonn Holmes''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|i\u02d0|m|\u0259|n}}; born 3 December 1959)<ref name=HonDeg1>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/5141052.stm Holmes receives honorary degree] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331100522/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/5141052.stm |date=31 March 2009 }} BBC News, 4 July 2006</ref> is an Northern Irish journalist<ref>https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/701066/This-Morning-Potato-Famine-joke-Alice-Beer-Eamonn-Holmes-Ruth-Langsford</ref> and broadcaster. Holmes co-presented ''[[List of GMTV programmes#GMTV|GMTV]]'' for twelve years between 1993 and 2005, before presenting ''[[Sunrise (Sky News)|Sky News Sunrise]]'' for eleven years between 2005 and 2016. Since 2006, he has co-hosted ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' with his wife [[Ruth Langsford]] on Fridays and during school holidays.\n\nHe has also presented ''[[Eamonn & Ruth: How the Other Half Lives|How the Other Half Lives]]'' (2015\u2013present) and ''[[It's Not Me, It's You (game show)|It's Not Me, It's You]]'' (2016) for [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]. Holmes is an advocate of numerous charities and causes including [[Dogs Trust]], Variety GB and Northern Ireland Kidney Patients' Association.\n\nEamonn Holmes has lost a First Tier Tribunal (FTT) appeal in February 2020 regarding his status as a freelancer under IR35 rules, with the judge determining his contract with ITV\u2019s ''This Morning'' programme amounted to employment. Giving evidence in the proceedings, Holmes described himself as \"..the best live television presenter in the country.\"<ref>RWG Limited v. Commissioners HMRC TC/2017/03624</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nHolmes was educated at Holy Family Primary School <ref name=PassFail>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/passedfailed-an-education-in-the-life-of-eamonn-holmes-television-presenter-454876.html Passed/Failed: An education in the life of Eamonn Holmes, television presenter] ''The Independent'', 28 June 2007</ref> and [[St Malachy's College]],<ref name=HonDeg1/> Belfast. He then studied journalism at the [[Dublin Business School|Dublin College of Business Studies]].<ref name=\"PassFail\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nBefore entering broadcasting, Holmes worked for a [[Dublin]]-based business magazine. In 1979, he joined [[UTV (TV channel)|Ulster Television]], the ITV franchise contractor for Northern Ireland working as a host and reporter for the station's ''Farming Ulster'' programme. Afterwards, he teamed up with Ulster Television's sports reporters, Leslie Dawes (1922\u20132014) and [[Jackie Fullerton]], to assist in covering sporting events in the province.\n\nIn 1982, Holmes was moved into news and current affairs reporting when he was tasked to anchor Ulster Television's flagship ''Good Evening Ulster'' programme. Holmes succeeded [[Gloria Hunniford]] who had presented the show since its launch in 1979. Holmes was the third choice to present the programme after trial runs by news reporters Gary Gillespie and Gerry Kelly.\n\nIn addition to his news and current affairs role, Holmes has also hosted other Ulster Television productions, including ''Miss Northern Ireland'' gala specials in 1985 and 1986. With Ulster Television, he won a Hometown Radio Award. He departed in 1986 to join the BBC.  At the [[New Broadcasting House (Manchester)|corporation's Manchester studios]], Holmes worked as a presenter on the daytime ''[[Open Air]]'' programme which was broadcast nationally on [[BBC One|BBC1]].\n\n===Television presenting===\nHolmes has presented coverage of [[snooker]], [[horse racing]] and [[darts]] on television.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/northern-ireland/2336055/Sport-in-My-World-Eamonn-Holmes.html Sport in My World: Eamonn Holmes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008210914/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/northern-ireland/2336055/Sport-in-My-World-Eamonn-Holmes.html |date=8 October 2013 }} ''The Daily Telegraph'', 28 April 2006</ref><ref name=FG1>[https://www.itv.com/Entertainment/chatandtalent/FeelgoodFactor/Participants/EamonnHolmes/default.html Eamonn Holmes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315234508/https://www.itv.com/Entertainment/chatandtalent/FeelgoodFactor/Participants/EamonnHolmes/default.html |date=15 March 2012 }} Feelgood Factor, ITV, 2009.</ref> He was also the presenter of ITV's coverage of the [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Phil Taylor]] vs. [[Raymond van Barneveld]] showdown at the [[Wembley Conference Centre]] in 1999.<ref name=BFI1>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/individual/176798?view=credit&page=2 Filmography HOLMES, Eamonn] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022030050/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/individual/176798?view=credit&page=2 |date=22 October 2012 }} BFI \u2013 Film & TV Database</ref><ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/674012 SIMPLY THE BEST PHIL TAYLOR V RAYMOND VAN BARNEVELD] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022030114/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/674012 |date=22 October 2012 }}  BFI \u2013 Film & TV Database</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Holmes started working at ''[[GMTV]]'', hosting the first show on 1 January 1993 with [[Anne Davies (British journalist)|Anne Davies]]. He had a falling-out with his subsequent co-host [[Anthea Turner]]; however, they were reunited on a BBC NI show entitled ''The Friday Show'' in 2009, where they seemed to get on better.{{Citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\nHolmes presented the [[BBC]] [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery]] game show ''[[Jet Set (game show)|Jet Set]]'' between 2001 and 2007.\n\nIn April 2005, he left ''[[GMTV]]'', stating the show had run out of real news and became celebrity obsessed shortly before his departure.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/4488781.stm Holmes bids farewell to GMTV sofa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080901015157/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/4488781.stm |date=1 September 2008 }} BBC News, 27 April 2005</ref>\n\nAfter leaving ''[[GMTV]]'' in April 2005, Holmes joined [[Sky News]] six months later to present the new-look ''[[Sunrise (Sky News)|Sunrise]]'' programme. He initially hosted the show with [[Lorna Dunkley]] between October 2005 and January 2007, then with [[Charlotte Hawkins]] from 2007 to 2014. Hawkins defected to [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in March 2014 and was replaced by [[Isabel Webster]]. In September 2016, Holmes announced his departure from the programme after eleven years.\n\nHolmes presented ''[[SUDO-Q]]'', a [[BBC]] quiz show between December 2005 and March 2007.\n\nIn 2006, Holmes began presenting [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] daytime programme ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' on Friday mornings. He works on the show, co-presenting ''This Morning'' with Langsford every Friday and Monday to Thursday during school holidays.\n\nIn 2006, Holmes hosted US game show ''[[The Rich List (U.S. game show)|The Rich List]]''. In 2009, Holmes co-presented the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''The Feelgood Factor'' with [[Myleene Klass]]. He presented eight episodes of ''[[Songs of Praise]]'' from 2009 until 2014. In 2010, Eamonn guest presented an episode of ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''.\n\nIn 2014, Holmes and [[Ruth Langsford]] co-hosted a 10-part [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] daytime game show, ''[[Gift Wrapped (game show)|Gift Wrapped]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week34/gift-wrapped#.U-CvnuNdXY8|title=Gift Wrapped Episode 1|website=Itv.com|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006073021/https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week34/gift-wrapped#.U-CvnuNdXY8|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a583302/eamonn-holmes-ruth-langsford-to-host-new-itv-daytime-quiz.html#~oJDr8r7NF1psmJ|title=Eamonn, Ruth to host ITV quiz show|date=10 July 2014|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924225835/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a583302/eamonn-holmes-ruth-langsford-to-host-new-itv-daytime-quiz.html#~oJDr8r7NF1psmJ|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2015, Holmes and Langsford presented a six-part factual series for [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] entitled ''[[Eamonn & Ruth: How the Other Half Lives]]''. The programme returned for a second series in September 2016 and a third in June 2017.<ref>[http://about.channel5.com/node/2143]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Holmes presented [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] panel show ''[[It's Not Me, It's You (game show)|It's Not Me, It's You]]''. [[Vicky Pattison]] and [[Kelly Brook]] were team captains on the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a792871/eamonn-holmes-will-host-a-cheeky-channel-5-panel-show-about-dating/|title=Eamonn Holmes to host \"cheeky\" panel show about dating|date=4 May 2016|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107025054/https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a792871/eamonn-holmes-will-host-a-cheeky-channel-5-panel-show-about-dating/|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sroaudiences.com/application.asp?show_id=1717|title=Pre-registration for IT'S NOT ME, IT'S YOU with KELLY BROOK, VICKY PATTISON & EAMONN HOLMES from SRO Audiences|website=sroaudiences.com|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107025615/http://sroaudiences.com/application.asp?show_id=1717|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHolmes has guest presented numerous episodes of ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' since April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a825573/eamonn-holmes-good-morning-britain-breakfast-tv-return-piers-morgan-ruth-langsford/|title=Eamonn Holmes made his breakfast TV return this morning|date=10 April 2017|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728211259/https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a825573/eamonn-holmes-good-morning-britain-breakfast-tv-return-piers-morgan-ruth-langsford/|archivedate=28 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a829182/eamonn-holmes-replacing-piers-morgan-good-morning-britain-half-term/|title=Eamonn Holmes replacing Piers Morgan on GMB|date=25 May 2017|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920082930/https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a829182/eamonn-holmes-replacing-piers-morgan-good-morning-britain-half-term/|archivedate=20 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFrom March 2018, Holmes co-presented ''Do the Right Thing'' with [[Ruth Langsford]] on [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]].\n\n===Other television work===\nIn 2001, Holmes appeared on ''[[Blankety Blank|Lily Savage's Blankety Blank]]''.<ref name=\"blanketyblank\">{{cite episode|series=Lily Savage's Blankety Blank|airdate=18 February 2001|network=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. Repeated 25 August 2016 on [[Challenge TV]]}}</ref><ref name=\"blanketyblank2\">{{cite episode|series=Lily Savage's Blankety Blank|network=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]|airdate=3 June 2001}}</ref> In 2013, Holmes was a judge on the [[CBBC]] ''[[Blue Peter]]'' talent search for a new presenter, ''Blue Peter \u2013 You Decide''.\n\nHolmes has made four appearances on the long-running game show ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to be a Millionaire?]]''. The first time, he played with [[Alex Ferguson]] on 25 December 2004. On 1 September 2007, he played with [[Kay Burley]]. On 20 May 2012, he returned with [[Ruth Langsford]] by his side. Finally, on 19 December 2013, to celebrate the end of ''Millionaire'' on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], Holmes re-appeared on the show with [[Alex Ferguson]]. Holmes has also appeared on celebrity editions of game shows including ''[[Fifteen to One]]'', ''[[Call My Bluff]]'', ''[[All Star Mr & Mrs]]'', ''[[Tipping Point: Lucky Stars]]'', ''[[Catchphrase (UK game show)|Catchphrase]]'' and ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]''.\n\nHolmes has also made regular appearances on ''[[Big Brother's Bit on the Side]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigbrother.channel5.com/day-24-eamonn-holmes-tries-break|title=Day 24: Eamonn Holmes tries to break in \u2013 Celebrity Big Brother|publisher=Channel 5|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905190027/http://bigbrother.channel5.com/day-24-eamonn-holmes-tries-break|archivedate=5 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and in 2015, he was heavily tipped as a housemate for ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 16]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-08-27/celebrity-big-brother-summer-2015--whos-going-into-the-house|title=Celebrity Big Brother summer 2015 \u2013 who's going into the house?|website=Radio Times|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919081242/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-08-27/celebrity-big-brother-summer-2015--whos-going-into-the-house|archivedate=19 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2016, he appeared in two episodes of ''[[Diddy TV]]'' on [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} He has been a panellist on numerous episodes of ''[[Through the Keyhole]]'' and appeared in ITV's ''[[ITV Specials|Guess the Star]]'' in 2017. Since November 2017, he has provided the voiceover for ''Biggleton'' on [[CBeebies]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===Radio===\nHolmes' foray into radio broadcasting was at Downtown Radio, Northern Ireland's first commercial independent radio station, in the late 1980s.\n\nFrom around 2003, Holmes presented ''The Eamonn Holmes Show'' on [[BBC Radio 5 Live|Radio 5 Live]] on Saturday mornings between 9 and 11&nbsp;am for 6 years, last airing on 30 May 2009 as Holmes' contract with the [[BBC]] was not renewed.<ref>{{cite news | title=Danny Baker and Christian O'Connell to front new shows on BBC Radio 5 Live | work=The Guardian | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/may/08/danny-baker-christian-oconnell-5-live | date=8 May 2009 | accessdate=23 May 2009 | first=John | last=Plunkett | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224120931/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/may/08/danny-baker-christian-oconnell-5-live | archivedate=24 December 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2005, Holmes hosted his own programme on London radio station [[Magic 105.4]].<ref name=SurreyL/>\n\nFor a few weeks in 2008, Holmes took over [[Michael Parkinson]]'s Sunday morning show on [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]].<ref name=SurreyL>[http://surrey.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/eamonn-holmes--this-is-his-surrey-life-10113/ Eamonn Holmes \u2013 This is his Surrey life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100513053106/http://surrey.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/eamonn-holmes--this-is-his-surrey-life-10113/ |date=13 May 2010 }} Surrey Life, March 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Holmes presented his own radio show on [[Talkradio]]. The show was called ''Let's Talk With Eamonn Holmes'' and was broadcast on Saturdays from 6{{nbsp}}am to 8{{nbsp}}am and Sundays from 11{{nbsp}}am to 1{{nbsp}}pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/news/a786057/eamonn-holmes-to-present-new-show-on-talkradio-and-jon-holmes-will-host-afternoons/|title=Eamonn Holmes to present new show on talkRADIO|date=8 March 2016|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107013435/https://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/news/a786057/eamonn-holmes-to-present-new-show-on-talkradio-and-jon-holmes-will-host-afternoons/|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://talkradio.co.uk/radio/schedule/|title=talkRADIO Schedule|website=Talkradio.co.uk|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903175720/http://talkradio.co.uk/radio/schedule|archivedate=3 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSince January 2018, Holmes has presented the weekday show on [[Talkradio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://talkradio.co.uk/news/welcome-holmes-eamonn-holmes-joins-all-new-talkradio-18011222965|title=Eamonn Holmes joins all-new talkRADIO|work=talkradio.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nHolmes writes a column for ''[[The Sunday People|The People]]'' newspaper.<ref>[http://www.people.co.uk/news/eammonholmes/ Eamonn  \u2013 Man of the people] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070110172155/http://www.people.co.uk/news/eammonholmes/ |date=10 January 2007 }} ''The People''</ref> His [[autobiography]] was released in May 2006.<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/This-My-Life-Eamonn-Autogiography/dp/075287523X This Is My Life: Eamonn Holmes: The Autogiography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070909053539/http://www.amazon.co.uk/This-My-Life-Eamonn-Autogiography/dp/075287523X |date=9 September 2007 }} Amazon.com</ref> The autobiography is called ''This is MY Life'', a reference to another famous Irish Eamonn \u2013 [[Eamonn Andrews]], after whom he was named.<ref name=SurreyL/><ref name=LifeMed/> The book reveals some of what occurred behind the scenes during his tenure at GMTV.<ref name=LifeMed/>\n\n==Controversies==\nHolmes was accused of being opposed to [[LGBT parenting]] when he told two gay interviewees in a 2000 GMTV episode that \"You are not meant to have children. You are going against nature!\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Dad'll do nicely|last1=Simon|first1=Jane|last2=McIver|first2=Brian|newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|date=21 July 2010}}</ref> American illusionist [[David Blaine]] appeared on the show on 29 August 2001. Holmes cites this interview with Blaine as the most awkward moment of his professional career and one of TV's bloopers when he refused to speak and gave him the \"[[evil eye]]\".<ref name=LifeMed>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/eamonn-holmes-my-life-in-media-407338.html Eamonn Holmes: My Life In Media] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925091738/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/eamonn-holmes-my-life-in-media-407338.html |date=25 September 2015 }} ''The Independent'', 10 July 2006</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, [[Jon Culshaw]] appeared as Holmes on ''[[The Impressions Show with Culshaw and Stephenson|The Impressions Show]]'' in a series of three comedy sketches in which he was portrayed as having an appetite so uncontrollable that he eats a sofa, flowers and even a guest ([[Frankie Dettori]]), using the catchphrase 'I was fierce hungry, so I was'. Even though Holmes had interviewed Culshaw and his co-star [[Debra Stephenson]] on ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' to promote the show,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/clips/p005cb2d/the_impressions_show_with_culshaw_and_stephenson_eamonn_holmes_eat_your_heart_out/ Eamonn Holmes Eat Your Heart Out] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725083619/http://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/clips/p005cb2d/the_impressions_show_with_culshaw_and_stephenson_eamonn_holmes_eat_your_heart_out/ |date=25 July 2010 }} The Impressions Show with Culshaw and Stephenson, BBC Comedy, 27 November 2009</ref> after the programme aired the presenter instructed his lawyers to send a letter of complaint to the BBC.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/7897143/Eamonn-Holmes-threatens-BBC-with-legal-action-after-comedy-show-mocks-his-weight.html Eamonn Holmes threatens BBC with legal action after comedy show mocks his weight] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722063727/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/7897143/Eamonn-Holmes-threatens-BBC-with-legal-action-after-comedy-show-mocks-his-weight.html |date=22 July 2010 }} ''The Daily Telegraph'', 19 July 2010</ref> The letter resulted in an apology from the BBC along with a withdrawal of any future comedy sketches featuring Holmes.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-10684974 BBC apologises to Eamonn Holmes over weight jibes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722160408/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-10684974 |date=22 July 2010 }} BBC News, 19 July 2010</ref> Both the complaint itself and the outcome of Holmes's legal action drew generally unfavourable criticism from media observers and online commentators.<ref>Julie Burchill [http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/opinion/columnists/julie-burchill-if-eamonn-holmes-cant-see-the-funny-side-of-fatness-he-should-lay-off-the-pies-14881914.html If Eamonn Holmes can't see the funny side of fatness, he should lay off the pies] ''The Belfast Telegraph'', 21 July 2010</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lostinshowbiz/2010/jul/22/bbc-bans-eamonn-holmes-jokes Eamonn Holmes gets the BBC jokes eating away at him banned] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305010304/https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lostinshowbiz/2010/jul/22/bbc-bans-eamonn-holmes-jokes |date=5 March 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 22 July 2010</ref><ref>Andrew M Brown  [http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/andrewmcfbrown/100047695/if-eamonn-holmes-doesnt-like-the-bbc-teasing-him-theres-a-simple-solution/ If Eamonn Holmes doesn't like the BBC teasing him about being fat, there's a simple solution] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724072349/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/andrewmcfbrown/100047695/if-eamonn-holmes-doesnt-like-the-bbc-teasing-him-theres-a-simple-solution/ |date=24 July 2010 }} ''The Daily Telegraph'', 19 July 2010</ref>\n\nWhile presenting ''This Morning'' in October 2011, Holmes described singer [[Jonathan Wilkes]] as \"retarded\" on air. He later apologised after complaints and calls for him to be sacked. Holmes said: \"I have to say sorry to three or four of you who are upset because I used the word retarded. You seem to have taken it personally or think I am being insulting. I would never want to do that. There is this man who has an autistic child and said I insulted his child. I would never use it in that context. Sorry if that caused you offence\".<ref>O'Connor, Niall. [http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/eamonn-says-sorry-for-calling-guest-retard-2900359.html Eamonn says sorry for calling guest 'retard']. herald.i.e. 8 October 2011.</ref><ref>Small, Louise. [http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/eamonn-holmes-sorry-for-retarded-comment-16061013.html Eamonn Holmes sorry for 'retarded' comment]. ''The Belfast Telegraph''. 8 October 2011.</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, Holmes provoked criticism by suggesting that a rape victim should take taxis in future, leading to accusations of [[victim blaming]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Eamonn Holmes cricised for controversial rape comment|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/8852782/Eamonn-Holmes-cricised-for-controversial-rape-comment.html|accessdate=27 October 2011|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=27 October 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028134427/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/8852782/Eamonn-Holmes-cricised-for-controversial-rape-comment.html|archivedate=28 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 May 2016, Eamonn Holmes provoked criticism by comparing an attack by [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham fans]] to the [[Hillsborough disaster]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nEamonn Holmes was reprimanded by [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] producers after making remarks about [[Meghan Markle]]. This followed a complaint to [[Ofcom]] criticising his use of the term \"uppity\" as a racist term to describe Meghan Markle. He then followed this up in an interview on Talkradio where he called her \"awful, woke, weak, manipulative, spoilt and irritating\" and said he didn't think he would like her, despite admitting he has never met her in person.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weatherby|first=Bronwen|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/eamonn-holmes-meghan-markle-royals-sussex-a4331791.html|title=Eamonn Holmes calls Meghan Markle 'spoilt, weak, woke and manipulative' in scathing rant|work=Evening Standard|date=10 January 2020|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, Holmes appeared to perpetuate the conspiracy theory that the building of [[5G]] masts had led to the [[Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Baynes|first=Chris|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/tv-radio/eamonn-holmes-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-this-morning-itv-a9462461.html|title=Eamonn Holmes fans flames of 5G coronavirus conspiracies by saying \u2018it suits state narrative\u2019 for media to dismiss them|work=The Independent|date=13 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> In a feature on ''This Morning'' surrounding \"Fake News\" related to the virus Holmes stated that he \"didn't accept mainstream media immediately slapping it down\". He suggested that it was a sign of an \"enquiring mind\" to investigate the theory which had already been much debunked by experts. However, Holmes said that \"it suits the state narrative\" to deny the theory.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robinson|first=Gregory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/13/eamonn-holmes-says-5g-coronavirus-claims-may-not-be-false|title=Eamonn Holmes criticised for giving credence to Covid-19 5G conspiracy theory|work=The Guardian|date=13 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Ofcom soon announced that it was investigating the incident. In a statement on the following day's programme, Holmes read a statement which stated \"there is no connection between the present national health emergency and 5G, and to suggest otherwise would be wrong and indeed it could be dangerous.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52279109|title=Coronavirus: Ofcom assesses Eamonn Holmes 5G comments after complaints|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Ofcom received more than 400 complaints about the incident and later issued guidance to ITV on its coverage of the pandemic. On the two-way with Alice Beer, Ofcom commented: \"In our view, Eamonn Holmes\u2019 ambiguous comments were ill-judged and risked undermining viewers\u2019 trust in advice from public authorities and scientific evidence.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobitt|first=Charlotte|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52358920|title=Ofcom sanctions London Live over 'potentially harmful' David Icke interview on coronavirus|work=Press Gazette|date=20 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1985, Holmes married his first wife, Gabrielle Holmes, with whom he has three children, Declan, Rebecca and Niall. They separated in 1995, due to Holmes' father's death and [[journalism]] career taking a toll on their marriage.<ref name=MarriedBT/> In 1997, Holmes began dating [[Ruth Langsford]], but the couple kept their relationship secret out of respect for Gabrielle and their children. \n\nIn 2002, Langsford gave birth to their son, Jack Alexander Holmes. Holmes and Gabrielle eventually [[divorce]]d in 2005.\n\nOn 26 June 2010, Holmes married Langsford at Elvetham Hall, near [[Hartley Wintney]], [[Hampshire]].<ref name=MarriedBT>[http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/holmes-and-partner-ruth-walk-down-aisle-14856209.html Holmes and partner Ruth walk down aisle] ''The Belfast Telegraph'', 26 June 2010</ref> The couple sold exclusive rights to report on the wedding ceremony and the reception to ''[[Hello!]]'' magazine in a deal that saw the publication feature the event over two issues, in July 2010.<ref>[http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/201006283767/eamonn-holmes/hello-wedding/exclusive/1/ Only in Hello! Eamonn and Ruth marry surrounded by showbiz friends] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919053004/http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/201006283767/eamonn-holmes/hello-wedding/exclusive/1/ |date=19 September 2011 }} Hello!, 28 June 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Holmes was awarded an [[honorary degree]] by [[Queen's University Belfast]].<ref name=HonDeg1/><ref>[http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/incoming/ulsterborn-tv-presenter-eamonn-holmes-was-today-presented-with-an-honorary-degree-from-queens-university-13534602.html Ulster-born TV presenter Eamonn Holmes was today presented with an honorary degree from Queen's University] ''The Belfast Telegraph'', 3 July 2006</ref> He has also received an honorary degree from the [[University of Staffordshire]].<ref>[http://www.staffs.ac.uk/about_us/about_the_university/doctors/1986-2005/ Honorary Doctors 1986 \u2013 2005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705055323/http://www.staffs.ac.uk/about_us/about_the_university/doctors/1986-2005/ |date=5 July 2008 }} University of Staffordshire</ref>\n\nHolmes is a supporter of Manchester United FC<ref name=Wayne>[http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/imported/he-has-a-passion-for-john-wayne-movies-13872491.html \"He has a passion for John Wayne movies\"] ''The Belfast Telegraph'', 26 April 1996, i'm also Gordon's minyon</ref> In December 2005, he opened the eulogies at the funeral of Northern Irish footballer [[George Best]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4493898.stm Final farewell to football legend] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217015424/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4493898.stm |date=17 February 2009 }} BBC News, 3 December 2005</ref>\n\nHolmes and Langsford are patrons of [[Dogs Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialeamonnholmes.com/charity|title=Charity \u2013 Eamonn Holmes|first=Eamonn|last=Holmes|website=Eamonn Holmes|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526184142/http://www.officialeamonnholmes.com/charity|archivedate=26 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the couple adopted their dog, Maggie from the charity in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dogstrust.org.uk/mediacentre/newsreleases/pr11harefieldmaggieandeamonnholmes.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-09-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103091603/http://www.dogstrust.org.uk/mediacentre/newsreleases/pr11harefieldmaggieandeamonnholmes.aspx |archivedate=3 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2014, the couple supported the Dementia Friends campaign, which is an [[Alzheimer's Society]] initiative.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.alzheimers.org.uk/site/scripts/news_article.php?newsID=2322 |title=Alzheimer's Society achieves one million Dementia Friends ambition |date=21 February 2015 |website=[[Alzheimer's Society]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223214035/http://www.alzheimers.org.uk/site/scripts/news_article.php?newsID=2322 |archivedate=23 February 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Holmes became a celebrity ambassador for the children's charity, Variety GB.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.org.uk/news/2015/04/eamonn-holmes-inducted-celebrity-ambassador-variety|title=Eamonn Holmes Inducted as Celebrity Ambassador for Variety|date=30 April 2015|website=Variety.org.uk|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107005230/https://www.variety.org.uk/news/2015/04/eamonn-holmes-inducted-celebrity-ambassador-variety|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charitytoday.co.uk/new-variety-ambassador-eamonn-to-host-celebratory-launch-event/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150531102211/http://www.charitytoday.co.uk/new-variety-ambassador-eamonn-to-host-celebratory-launch-event/ |archivedate=31 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In January 2016, he became a patron of Northern Ireland Kidney Patients' Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfastlive.co.uk/news/belfast-news/eamonn-holmes-made-patron-northern-10779796|title=Eamonn Holmes made patron of Northern Ireland kidney charity|first=Jilly|last=Beattie|date=23 January 2016|website=Belfastlive.co.uk|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107010216/http://www.belfastlive.co.uk/news/belfast-news/eamonn-holmes-made-patron-northern-10779796|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Television\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Channel\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1986\u20131989\n| ''[[Open Air (TV series)|Open Air]]''\n| Presenter\n| [[BBC One]]\n| Series 1\u20133\n|-\n| 1993\u20132005\n| ''[[GMTV]]''\n| Co-presenter\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| \n|-\n| 2001\u20132007\n| ''[[Jet Set (game show)|Jet Set]]''\n| Presenter\n| [[BBC One]]\n| 8 series\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Would You Pass The 11+''\n| Co-presenter\n| [[BBC Northern Ireland]]\n| 1 episode; with [[Christine Bleakley]]\n|-\n| 2005\u20132007\n| ''[[SUDO-Q]]''\n| Presenter\n| [[BBC One]]/[[BBC Two]]\n| 4 series\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2005\n| ''[[Ant & Dec's Gameshow Marathon]]''\n| Contestant\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| Series 1\n|-\n| ''[[The Sunday Night Project]]''\n| Guest presenter\n| [[Channel 4]]\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2005\u20132016\n| ''[[Sky News Sunrise|Sunrise]]''\n| Main anchor\n| [[Sky News]]\n| Breakfast news programme\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[The Rich List (U.S. game show)|The Rich List]]''\n| Presenter\n| [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| American game show\n|-\n| 2006\u2013\n| ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''\n| Co-presenter\n| rowspan=2|[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| Fridays and school holidays; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''The Feelgood Factor''\n| Co-presenter\n| 1 series; with [[Myleene Klass]]\n|-\n| 2009\u20132014\n| ''[[Songs of Praise]]''\n| Presenter\n| rowspan=2|[[BBC One]]\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''\n| Guest presenter\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Blue Peter \u2013 You Decide''\n| Judge\n| [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]]\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Gift Wrapped (game show)|Gift Wrapped]]''\n| Co-presenter\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| 1 series; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n| 2014\u20132018\n| ''[[Big Brother's Bit on the Side]]''\n| Regular pannellist\n| rowspan=3|[[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]\n| 24 episodes\n|-\n| 2015\u2013\n| ''[[Eamonn & Ruth: How The Other Half Lives]]''\n| Co-presenter\n| 3 series; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[It's Not Me, It's You (game show)|It's Not Me, It's You]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/news/2101/eamonn_holmes_panel_show/|title=Eamonn Holmes to host Channel 5 panel show|first=British Comedy|last=Guide|date=29 April 2016|website=Comedy.co.uk|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107032217/https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/news/2101/eamonn_holmes_panel_show/|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| Presenter\n| 1 series\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2017\u2013\n| ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''\n| Guest presenter\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| 14 episodes \n|-\n| ''Biggleton''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/eamonn-holmes-over-moon-surprised-11275487|title=Eamonn Holmes bags surprising new job \u2013 after fluffing the audition|first=Seamus|last=Duff|date=2 October 2017|website=Daily Mirror|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002215940/https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/eamonn-holmes-over-moon-surprised-11275487|archivedate=2 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| Narrator\n| [[CBeebies]]\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Eamonn & Ruth's 7 Year Itch''\n| Co-presenter\n| rowspan=2|[[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]\n| Two-part documentary; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n| 2018\u2013\n| ''Do The Right Thing with Eamonn and Ruth''\n| Co-presenter\n| 1 series; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n|2018\n| ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)|Love Island: The Reunion]]''\n| Guest\n| [[ITV2]]\n| 1 episode; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n| 2018\u2013\n| ''[[How To Get A Good Night\u2019s Sleep]]''\n| Co-presenter\n| [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]\n| 1 series; with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Celebrity Gogglebox]]''\n| TV Watcher\n| [[Channel 4]]\n| with [[Ruth Langsford]]\n|}\n;Film\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]''\n| Bigmouth Executive & Forge (Re-dubbed voice)\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys D'Movie]]''\n| [[RT\u00c9]] newsreader\n| Cameo role\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Wonder Park]]''\n| Uncle Tony (Re-dubbed voice)\n| \n|}\n\n;Radio\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2003\u20132009\n| ''[[BBC Radio 5 Live|The Eamonn Holmes Show]]''\n| Presenter\n| Sports show on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]\n|-\n| 2005\u2013??\n| ''[[Magic 105.4 FM|Sunday Afternoons]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/491109/magic-fm-signs-eamonn-holmes-present-sunday-show|title=Magic FM signs Eamonn Holmes to present Sunday show|website=Campaignlive.co.uk|accessdate=29 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304073511/http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/491109/magic-fm-signs-eamonn-holmes-present-sunday-show|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| Presenter\n| Sundays, 4{{snd}}7{{nbsp}}pm on [[Magic 105.4 FM|Magic FM]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''The Michael Parkinson Show''\n| Guest presenter\n| [[BBC Radio 2]] show\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Let's Talk with Eamonn Holmes''\n| Presenter\n| Sundays, 11{{nbsp}}am{{snd}}1{{nbsp}}pm on [[Talkradio]]\n|-\n| 2018\u20132020\n| ''Drivetime with Eamonn Holmes''\n| Presenter\n| Weekdays, 4{{snd}}7{{nbsp}}pm on [[Talkradio]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and honours==\nHolmes was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to broadcasting in the [[2018 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2017-12-29/ringo-starr-and-barry-gibb-to-be-knighted-in-new-year-honours/|title=Ringo Starr and Barry Gibb knighted in New Year Honours|work=ITV News}}</ref> He collected his OBE from [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 1 June 2018.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year 